## 1. Introduction

Sentiment Analysis is a Natural Language Processing (NLP) technique used to determine whether a piece of text expresses a positive, negative, or neutral sentiment. It is widely used in applications like product reviews, social media analysis, and customer feedback systems.

This project implements a simple sentiment analysis model using the Naive Bayes algorithm and a small custom dataset.

---

## 2. Objective

* To build a basic sentiment classification model.
* To classify text into Positive, Negative, and Neutral categories.
* To understand how machine learning works with text data.

---

## 3. Tools and Technologies Used

* Programming Language: Python
* Libraries:

  * scikit-learn
  * CountVectorizer
  * Multinomial Naive Bayes

---

## 4. Methodology

### 4.1 Data Collection

A small dataset of sentences was manually created and labeled into three categories:

* Positive
* Negative
* Neutral

### 4.2 Data Preprocessing

The text data is converted into numerical format using the Bag of Words model with CountVectorizer.

### 4.3 Model Training

A Multinomial Naive Bayes classifier is trained using the processed data.

### 4.4 Testing and Evaluation

A test dataset is used to evaluate the model performance using accuracy score.

### 4.5 Prediction System

A user input system is implemented where users can enter a sentence and the model predicts:

* Sentiment label
* Probability of each class

---

## 5. Implementation

### 5.1 Feature Extraction

CountVectorizer converts text into a matrix of token counts.

### 5.2 Model Used

Multinomial Naive Bayes is used because it works well with text classification problems.

### 5.3 Evaluation Metric

Accuracy Score is used to measure model performance.

---

## 6. Results

The model was tested on a small dataset and achieved approximately:

Accuracy: ~80%

Example Predictions:

* "I love this movie" → Positive
* "This food is terrible" → Negative
* "Today is a normal day" → Neutral

---

## 7. Advantages

* Simple and easy to implement
* Fast training and prediction
* Works well for small datasets

---

## 8. Limitations

* Small dataset reduces accuracy
* Cannot understand context deeply
* Limited vocabulary
* May give incorrect results for complex sentences

---

## 9. Future Improvements

* Use a larger dataset
* Apply TF-IDF instead of CountVectorizer
* Use advanced models like Logistic Regression or Deep Learning
* Deploy as a web application

---

## 10. Conclusion

This project demonstrates how machine learning can be used for sentiment analysis. Although the model is basic, it provides a good understanding of text classification techniques and can be improved further for real-world applications.

